title: run-task skill should prefer local runner with agent roles for small/medium tasks and for entire projects too.
---
Problem
The run-task skill currently recommends external runners (opencode with zai-coding-plan/glm-5) for all tasks. This is heavyweight for smaller tasks and doesn't leverage clawq's native agent role/template system. For many backlog items, a local runner (subagent executing within clawq's own session context) would be more efficient and avoid external CLI dependencies.

Why this matters
- External runners (codex, claude, opencode, etc.) add friction: auth, session management, startup latency
- Many tasks don't need full coding CLI capabilities — they need reasoning, file ops, git, and backlog tools
- Local runner with agent roles would be faster for small/medium work and keeps session state in DB
- Reduces reliance on external quota/limits for routine work
- Aligns with B501 (local runner for cron) and the broader agent role/template ecosystem

Acceptance criteria
- run-task skill updated to prefer local runner for small/medium tasks (heuristics or explicit sizing)
- Local runner uses agent roles/templates (e.g., "coder" role with appropriate tool restrictions)
- Skill documents when to escalate to external coding runners (large/complex tasks)
- Existing opencode+zai-coding-plan path remains available as fallback/upgrade path
- Skill is refined and optimized overall (current guidance is verbose and could be sharper)

Notes
- Current skill recommends runner="opencode" model="zai-coding-plan/glm-5" universally
- Related: B501 (local runner for cron), B487 (runner aliases), B488 (follow-up prompts), I013 (planning mode via bg tasks)
- "Local runner" here means delegate/background_task with use_worktree=true but without external CLI — clawq spawns its own subagent with a defined role/template
- Future work: add explicit coding runner path for tasks requiring specialized coding tools/models

Note: we still want to use external runners to make use of the available models and their tooling/integraiton. These are best suited to bigger one-off tasks (eg a big clawq task from the backlog).

